  "summary": {
    "mean_abs_correlation_time_domain": 0.231,
    "mean_abs_correlation_frequency_domain": 0.2863,
    "finding": "The three diagnostics have distinct spectral signatures. CR concentrates power at high frequencies (2-3 year periods) across all three countries, while TV and Aitchison concentrate power at low frequencies (12-25 year periods). Mean absolute correlation across all country pairs: 0.231 (time domain), 0.286 (frequency domain) — both well below the 0.5 threshold for concern. CR has dominant power where TV is quiet, and vice versa. The diagnostics are spectrally independent: they respond to different temporal scales of structural change.",
    "implication_for_W1": "W-1 (diagnostic independence) is supported by spectral evidence. The three diagnostics are not redundant — they decompose structural change at different characteristic frequencies. TV captures slow secular trends and large shocks. Aitchison captures ratio restructuring at intermediate scales. CR captures fast coupling dynamics at 2-3 year cycles. This is consistent with the filter-bank interpretation: the SBP decomposes the composition, and CR measures cross-branch coherence — a fundamentally different quantity than inter-composition distance.",
    "scarborough_bluffs_principle": "Confound-to-signal ratio is scale-dependent. At annual resolution, the three diagnostics operate in different frequency bands, making them naturally independent. At finer resolutions (monthly, daily), spectral overlap and aliasing may reduce this independence. This analysis applies to annual EMBER data only.",
